                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d467">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/63</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Secretary of State to the <gloss type="from">Ambassador in
                            Great Britain</gloss>
                    </hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-20T19:00:00-05:00">
                        <hi rend="italic">August 20, 1914, 7 p.m.</hi>
                    </date>
                </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>Your telegram 405, August 18. Department advised that American shippers, though
                    expecting compensation for damages, desire now the release of grain cargoes
                    diverted to England and of the funds resulting from the sale of such cargoes.
                    Otherwise grain trade seriously blocked on account of money tied up, in England,
                    and shippers may decline to make further shipments in English vessels if present
                    policy is continued. Make immediate and strong representations on the specific
                    question of the release of funds and cargoes and press for most expeditious and
                    favorable reply. Cable results.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
